	</div><div class="blogs_entrybody" style="clear:both">
		Jon almost dropped his cell phone.<br/><br/>"What?  That's impossible.  There's no way you got into my facility in under twenty-four hours!" Jon exclaimed."We'll meet you in your office tomorrow morning.  Don't forget to have the other half of that check waiting." I said happily as I ended the phone conversation.<br/><br/>Scrap raised the small box in his hands in an attempt to read the label on the top of the box.<br/><br/>"FullBox Designs, Inc.  Box #4455.  Barcode number XXXXXXXXXXXXX." Scrap mumbled slowly, straining to read the characters in the limited light of passing street lights.<br/><br/>"Chief, this looks like a tape backup storage box of some sort." Scrap said.  "So why would a client hire us to attempt entry into his own facility and steal a box that he's been given custody of?" <br/><br/>"I don't even know the entire story on this.  When I visited Jon at the site he gave me a quick tour of the facility and said he wanted a physical security penetration test." I replied.<br/><br/>Scrap paused for a moment.  "Our methods were a bit dubious, wouldn't you say?" <br/><br/>"Perhaps." I said as I dropped Scrap off at his apartment complex.  "We'll know more tomorrow." <br/><br/>The next morning Scrap and I were seated in the office of Jonathan Allison, President of Allison Technologies, Inc.  <br/><br/>ATI was an information destruction company that specialized in paper shredding and media destruction.  ATI was originally a document management software company that was squeezed out of the market by several larger players.  Jonathan took a gamble and changed his business to information destruction.  <br/>ATI had their headquarters building in an industrial park, surrounded by other large warehouse-type buildings.  Jonathan was a hands-on type of guy and personally designed and oversaw all security system implementations for ATI.<br/><br/>Several days before, Jonathan had contacted me through a third party about performing a physical penetration test.  While I would have typically referred him to several private investigation firms that specialize in such matters, this one sounded very inviting, and the fee was right.  Jonathan wanted me to gain access to his building and remove a box from a storage room.  If I could pull of the engagement in less than forty-eight hours, I would earn my agreed upon fee plus a bonus of twenty-five percent.  This added incentive was the reason that I asked Scrap to join me in brainstorming the operation.<br/><br/>With only a cursory facility inspection by me and our knack for mischief, we had put our plan into motion, and in the end we were successful.<br/><br/>"Good Morning Chief." Jon said as he poured us all cups of piping-hot columbian goodness.  "So, I noticed that the box was gone when I came in, just as you said it would be.  My alarm didn't go off, and I have nothing on my security cameras.  How did you do it?"<br/><br/>Scrap unzipped his gym bag and placed the box on Jon's desk.<br/><br/><i><br/>"The weakness in your security program is shared by many companies in today's world: your employees, and your security procedures.  After our meeting the other morning, I asked Scrap to join me on this engagement.  At lunch time we noticed that many of your employees walked down the street to the corner deli.  <br/><br/>We entered the deli and saw approximately five employees sitting at various tables.  While Scrap and I pretended to be making up our minds on what we wanted to eat, one of your employees got up from her table and went into the restroom.  The employee left her purse on the table with another employee close by.  <br/><br/>Scrap noticed that her badge was clipped to the zipper of the purse.  While I distracted the other employee with questions on getting to the airport, Scrap grabbed the badge and placed it in his pocket.  I thanked the employee for her directions to the airport and we left the deli." </i>I said, glancing through my notes on a small notepad.<br/><br/>"You just walked into my facility, grabbed the box and left?" Jon asked in complete astonishment.<br/><br/>"Correct.  The badge was still active and provided Scrap with access to the loading dock door.  Successful entry into the door with a valid badge did not trigger an alarm system." <br/><br/>Jonathan grinned widely and sipped on his cup of coffee.  "Well, I have to say, that was impressive." <br/><br/>"Thank you." I replied as I handed Jonathan the stolen employee badge.  "You might want to find out why Bernice Clueless didn't report her badge missing." <br/><br/>"I'll be sure to do that. Well, you certainly earned this." Jon said as he handed me a company check with a very inviting dollar amount printed on it.  "However, this only confirmed to me a suspicion that I already had." <br/><br/>I glanced at Scrap.  Scrap raised his eyebrows in interest.<br/><br/>"I'm sorry.  If you knew you had security issues with your facility, why did you ask us to perform this test?" I queried.<br/><br/>"Because we're missing some boxes."<p><hr><table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
